{"title_page": "White-nosed coati", "text_new": "{{short description|Species of mammal}}\n{{For|the South American relative|South American coati}}{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |publisher=[[IUCN]] |title=Nasua narica |authors=Cuar\u00f3n, A. D., Helgen, K., Reid, F., Pino, J. & Gonz\u00e1lez-Maya, J. F. |year=2016 |volume=2016 |page=e.T41683A45216060 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-1.RLTS.T41683A45216060.en |url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/41683/45216060}}</ref>\n| image = Nasua narica -Costa Rica-8.jpg\n| image_caption = in [[Costa Rica]]\n| genus = Nasua\n| species = narica\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]],&nbsp;1766)\n| synonyms = ''Viverra narica'' {{small|(Linnaeus, 1766)}}\n| subdivision_ranks = Subspecies\n| subdivision_ref = <ref name=MSW3/>\n| subdivision = *''N. n. narica'' {{small|(Linnaeus, 1766)}}\n*''N. n. molaris'' {{small|Merriam, 1902}}\n*''[[Cozumel Island coati|N. n. nelsoni]]'' {{small|Merriam, 1901}}\n*''N. n. yucatanica'' {{small|J. A. Allen, 1904}}\n| range_map = White-nosed Coati area.png\n| range_map_caption = The native range of the white-nosed coati. <small>'''Note:''' Its [[Colombia|Colombian]] range is restricted to the far northwest (see [[#Habitat and range|text]]).</small>\n}}\n\nThe '''white-nosed coati''' (''Nasua narica'')<ref name=MSW3>{{MSW3 |id=14001625}}</ref>,  also known as the '''coatimundi''' ({{IPAc-en|k|o\u028a|\u02cc|\u0251\u02d0|t|\u1d7b|\u02c8|m|\u028c|n|d|i}}),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/41683/45216060|title=The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref><ref>[http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/accounts/Nasua_nasua/ Animal Diversity Web] at [[University of Michigan]].   \"Coatis are also referred to in some texts as coatimundis. The name coati or coatimundi is Tupian Indian in origin.\"</ref> is a species of [[coati]] and a member of the family [[Procyonidae]] (raccoons and their relatives). Local Spanish names for the species include '''''pizote''''', '''''antoon''''', and '''''tej\u00f3n''''', depending upon the region.<ref>\"Tej\u00f3n\", which means [[badger]], is mainly used in [[Mexico]].</ref> It weighs about {{convert|4|-|6|kg|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite book|author1=David J. Schmidly |author2=William B. Davis |title=The mammals of Texas |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QdlJ3SbwUIgC&pg=PA167 |accessdate=15 September 2011 |date=1 August 2004 |publisher=University of Texas Press |isbn=978-0-292-70241-7 |pages=167\u2013}}</ref> However, males are much larger than females: small females can weigh as little as {{convert|2.5|kg|abbr=on}}, while large males can weigh as much as {{convert|12.2|kg|abbr=on}}.<ref>[http://www.mnh.si.edu/mna/image_info.cfm?species_id=208 North American Mammals: Nasua narica]. Mnh.si.edu. Retrieved on 2011-09-15.</ref><ref>[http://wc.pima.edu/Bfiero/tucsonecology/animals/mamm_coat.htm Coati (Nasua narica)]. Wc.pima.edu. Retrieved on 2011-09-15.</ref> On average, the nose-to-tail length of the species is about {{convert|110|cm|ft|abbr=on}} with about half of that being the tail length.\n\n==Habitat and range==\n[[File:nasuanarica1.jpg|thumb|left|A white-nosed coati at [[Rinc\u00f3n de la Vieja Volcano National Park]] in [[Costa Rica]]]]\n[[File:Coati Nasua narica Side 2212px.jpg|thumb|left|A white-nosed coati hanging out at the [[Philadelphia Zoo]]]]\nWhite-nosed coatis inhabit wooded areas ([[Tropical and subtropical dry broadleaf forests|dry]] and [[Tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests|moist forests]]) of the Americas.  They are found at any altitude from sea level to {{convert|3000|m|ft|abbr=on}},<ref name=Reid>{{cite book |last1=Reid |first1=Fiona A. |year=1997 |title=A Field Guide to the Mammals of Central America and Southeast Mexico |pages=259\u2013260 |isbn=0-19-506400-3 |oclc= 34633350}}</ref> and from as far north as southeastern [[Arizona]] and [[New Mexico]], through [[Mexico]] and Central America, to far northwestern [[Colombia]] ([[Gulf of Urab\u00e1]] region, near Colombian border with [[Panama]]).<ref name=Decker>Decker, D. M. (1991). ''[http://biostor.org/cache/pdf/f8/c6/d7/f8c6d73ff3bab3dea9652afe0bb9b25f.pdf Systematics Of The Coatis, Genus Nasua (Mammalia, Procyonidae)].'' Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington 104: 370\u2013386</ref><ref name=GuzmanLenis>Guzman-Lenis, A. R. (2004). ''[http://scienti.colciencias.gov.co:8084/publindex/docs/articulos/0120-548X/2290574/2295170.pdf Preliminary Review of the Procyonidae in Colombia.]'' Acta Biol\u00f3gica Colombiana 9(1): 69\u201376</ref> There has been considerable confusion over its southern range limit,<ref>Eisenberg, J., and K. H. Redford (1999). ''Mammals of the Neotropcs: The Central Neotropics.'' Vol. 3, p. 288. {{ISBN|0-226-19541-4}}</ref> but specimen records from most of Colombia (only exception is far northwest) and [[Ecuador]] are all [[South American coati]]s.<ref name=Decker/><ref name=GuzmanLenis/>\n\nCoatis from [[Cozumel Island]] have been treated as a separate species, the [[Cozumel Island coati]], but the vast majority of recent authorities treat it as a subspecies, ''N. narica nelsoni'', of the white-nosed coati.<ref name=MSW3/><ref name=\"iucn\"/><ref name=Reid/><ref name=HMW>Kays, R. (2009). White-nosed Coati (Nasua narica), pp. 527\u2013528 in: Wilson, D. E., and R. A. Mittermeier, eds. (2009). ''[[Handbook of the Mammals of the World]].'' Vol. 1, Carnivores. {{ISBN|978-84-96553-49-1}}</ref> They are smaller than white-nosed coatis from the adjacent mainland (''N. n. yucatanica''), but when compared more widely to white-nosed coatis the difference in size is not as clear.<ref name=Decker/> The level of other differences also support its status as a subspecies rather than separate species.<ref name=Decker/>\n\nWhite-nosed coatis have also been found in the U.S. state of [[Florida]], where they are an introduced species. It is unknown precisely when introduction occurred; an early specimen in the [[Florida Museum of Natural History]], labeled an \"escaped captive\", dates to 1928. There are several later documented cases of coatis escaping captivity, and since the 1970s there have been a number of sightings, and several live and dead specimens of various ages have been found. These reports have occurred over a wide area of southern Florida, and there is probable evidence of breeding, indicating that the population is well established.<ref name=Simberloff>{{cite book |title= Strangers in Paradise: Impact and Management of Nonindigenous Species in Florida|last= Simberloff|first= Daniel|authorlink= Daniel Simberloff|author2=Don C. Schmitz |author3=Tom C. Brown |year= 1997|publisher= Island Press|isbn= 1-55963-430-8|page= 170|url= https://books.google.com/?id=rtrpSllq4SQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate= 29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Feeding habits==\n[[File:Nasua narica 02 MWNH 353.JPG|thumb|Skull of a white nosed coati]]\nThey are [[omnivore]]s, preferring small [[vertebrate]]s, [[fruit]]s, [[carrion]], [[insect]]s, [[snake]]s and [[egg (biology)|eggs]]. They can climb trees easily, where the tail is used for balance, but they are most often on the ground foraging. Their predators include [[Boidae|boa]]s, [[Bird of prey|raptor]]s, [[Felidae|hunting cats]], and [[Tayra]]s (''Eira barbara'').  They readily adapt to human presence; like [[raccoon]]s, they will raid campsites and trash receptacles.  They can be tamed easily, and have been verified experimentally to be quite [[Animal cognition|intelligent]].{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\n==Behavior==\n[[File:White nosed Coati.jpg|left|thumb|A white-nosed coati in a [[conservation area]] in [[Arenal Huetar Norte Conservation Area|Arenal, Costa Rica]]]]\nWhile the [[raccoon]] and ringtail are nocturnal, coatis are [[Diurnality|active by day]], retiring during the night to a specific tree and descending at dawn to begin their daily search for food. However, their habits are adjustable, and in areas where they are hunted by humans for food, or where they raid human settlements for their own food, they might become more [[Nocturnality|nocturnal]].  Adult males are [[Lone wolf (trait)|solitary]], but females and sexually immature males form [[Social unit|social groups]]. They use many vocal signals to [[Animal communication|communicate]] with one another, and also spend time grooming themselves and each other with their teeth and claws. During [[foraging]] times, the young cubs are left with a pair of babysitters, similar to [[meerkat]]s. The young males and even some females tend to [[Play fighting|play-fight]]. Many of the [[coati]]s will have short [[Combat|fights]] over food.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\nWhite-nosed coatis are known pollinators of the balsa tree, as observed in a study of a white-nosed coati population in Costa Rica. <ref name=Mora>Mora, Jos\u00e9 Manuel. (1999). ''[https://tropicalstudies.org/rbt/attachments/volumes/vol47-4/08_Mora_Nasua_narica.pdf White-nosed coati Nasua narica (Carnivora: Procyonidae) as a potentialpollinator of Ochroma pyramidale (Bombacaceae)].'' Revista de biologia tropical 47(4):719-721</ref> The coati were observed inserting their noses into the flowers of the tree and ingesting nectar, while the flower showed no subsequent signs of damage. Pollen from the flowers covers the face of the coati following feeding, and later disseminates through the surrounding forest following detachment. Scientists observed a dependent relationship between the balsa tree, which provides a critical resource of hydration and nutrition to the white-nosed coati when environment resources are scarce, and the coati, which increases proliferation of the tree through pollination.\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Nasua narica}}\n*[http://www.mnh.si.edu/mna/image_info.cfm?species_id=208 Smithsonian Institution \u2013 North American Mammals: Nasua narica]\n*[http://siwild.si.edu/content/animal-groups/other-carnivores/white-nosed-coati.htm?species=130 Smithsonian Wild: Nasua narica]\n\n{{Procyonidae nav}}\n{{Carnivora|C.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q754992}}\n\n[[Category:Procyonidae]]\n[[Category:Carnivorans of North America|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Carnivorans of Central America|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Carnivorans of South America|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Colombia|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Costa Rica|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Guatemala|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Mexico|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the United States|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Southwestern United States]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1766]]\n[[Category:Least concern biota of North America|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Least concern biota of South America|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Species of mammal}}\n{{For|the South American relative|South American coati}}{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Speciesbox\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref name=iucn>{{cite iucn |publisher=[[IUCN]] |title=Nasua narica |authors=Cuar\u00f3n, A. D., Helgen, K., Reid, F., Pino, J. & Gonz\u00e1lez-Maya, J. F. |year=2016 |volume=2016 |page=e.T41683A45216060 |doi=10.2305/IUCN.UK.2016-1.RLTS.T41683A45216060.en |url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/41683/45216060}}</ref>\n| image = Nasua narica -Costa Rica-8.jpg\n| image_caption = in [[Costa Rica]]\n| genus = Nasua\n| species = narica\n| authority = ([[Carl Linnaeus|Linnaeus]],&nbsp;1766)\n| synonyms = ''Viverra narica'' {{small|(Linnaeus, 1766)}}\n| subdivision_ranks = Subspecies\n| subdivision_ref = <ref name=MSW3/>\n| subdivision = *''N. n. narica'' {{small|(Linnaeus, 1766)}}\n*''N. n. molaris'' {{small|Merriam, 1902}}\n*''[[Cozumel Island coati|N. n. nelsoni]]'' {{small|Merriam, 1901}}\n*''N. n. yucatanica'' {{small|J. A. Allen, 1904}}\n| range_map = White-nosed Coati area.png\n| range_map_caption = The native range of the white-nosed coati. <small>'''Note:''' Its [[Colombia|Colombian]] range is restricted to the far northwest (see [[#Habitat and range|text]]).</small>\n}}\n\nThe '''white-nosed coati''' (''Nasua narica'')<ref name=MSW3>{{MSW3 |id=14001625}}</ref>,  also known as the '''coatimundi''' ({{IPAc-en|k|o\u028a|\u02cc|\u0251\u02d0|t|\u1d7b|\u02c8|m|\u028c|n|d|i}}),<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/species/41683/45216060|title=The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|website=IUCN Red List of Threatened Species|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref><ref>[http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/accounts/Nasua_nasua/ Animal Diversity Web] at [[University of Michigan]].   \"Coatis are also referred to in some texts as coatimundis. The name coati or coatimundi is Tupian Indian in origin.\"</ref> is a species of [[coati]] and a member of the family [[Procyonidae]] (raccoons and their relatives). Local Spanish names for the species include '''''pizote''''', '''''antoon''''', and '''''tej\u00f3n''''', depending upon the region.<ref>\"Tej\u00f3n\", which means [[badger]], is mainly used in [[Mexico]].</ref> It weighs about {{convert|4|-|6|kg|abbr=on}}.<ref>{{cite book|author1=David J. Schmidly |author2=William B. Davis |title=The mammals of Texas |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QdlJ3SbwUIgC&pg=PA167 |accessdate=15 September 2011 |date=1 August 2004 |publisher=University of Texas Press |isbn=978-0-292-70241-7 |pages=167\u2013}}</ref> However, males are much larger than females: small females can weigh as little as {{convert|2.5|kg|abbr=on}}, while large males can weigh as much as {{convert|12.2|kg|abbr=on}}.<ref>[http://www.mnh.si.edu/mna/image_info.cfm?species_id=208 North American Mammals: Nasua narica]. Mnh.si.edu. Retrieved on 2011-09-15.</ref><ref>[http://wc.pima.edu/Bfiero/tucsonecology/animals/mamm_coat.htm Coati (Nasua narica)]. Wc.pima.edu. Retrieved on 2011-09-15.</ref> On average, the nose-to-tail length of the species is about {{convert|110|cm|ft|abbr=on}} with about half of that being the tail length.\n\n==Habitat and range==\n[[File:nasuanarica1.jpg|thumb|left|A white-nosed coati at [[Rinc\u00f3n de la Vieja Volcano National Park]] in [[Costa Rica]]]]\n[[File:Coati Nasua narica Side 2212px.jpg|thumb|left|A white-nosed coati hanging out at the [[Philadelphia Zoo]]]]\nWhite-nosed coatis inhabit wooded areas ([[Tropical and subtropical dry broadleaf forests|dry]] and [[Tropical and subtropical moist broadleaf forests|moist forests]]) of the Americas.  They are found at any altitude from sea level to {{convert|3000|m|ft|abbr=on}},<ref name=Reid>{{cite book |last1=Reid |first1=Fiona A. |year=1997 |title=A Field Guide to the Mammals of Central America and Southeast Mexico |pages=259\u2013260 |isbn=0-19-506400-3 |oclc= 34633350}}</ref> and from as far north as southeastern [[Arizona]] and [[New Mexico]], through [[Mexico]] and Central America, to far northwestern [[Colombia]] ([[Gulf of Urab\u00e1]] region, near Colombian border with [[Panama]]).<ref name=Decker>Decker, D. M. (1991). ''[http://biostor.org/cache/pdf/f8/c6/d7/f8c6d73ff3bab3dea9652afe0bb9b25f.pdf Systematics Of The Coatis, Genus Nasua (Mammalia, Procyonidae)].'' Proceedings of the Biological Society of Washington 104: 370\u2013386</ref><ref name=GuzmanLenis>Guzman-Lenis, A. R. (2004). ''[http://scienti.colciencias.gov.co:8084/publindex/docs/articulos/0120-548X/2290574/2295170.pdf Preliminary Review of the Procyonidae in Colombia.]'' Acta Biol\u00f3gica Colombiana 9(1): 69\u201376</ref> There has been considerable confusion over its southern range limit,<ref>Eisenberg, J., and K. H. Redford (1999). ''Mammals of the Neotropcs: The Central Neotropics.'' Vol. 3, p. 288. {{ISBN|0-226-19541-4}}</ref> but specimen records from most of Colombia (only exception is far northwest) and [[Ecuador]] are all [[South American coati]]s.<ref name=Decker/><ref name=GuzmanLenis/>\n\nCoatis from [[Cozumel Island]] have been treated as a separate species, the [[Cozumel Island coati]], but the vast majority of recent authorities treat it as a subspecies, ''N. narica nelsoni'', of the white-nosed coati.<ref name=MSW3/><ref name=\"iucn\"/><ref name=Reid/><ref name=HMW>Kays, R. (2009). White-nosed Coati (Nasua narica), pp. 527\u2013528 in: Wilson, D. E., and R. A. Mittermeier, eds. (2009). ''[[Handbook of the Mammals of the World]].'' Vol. 1, Carnivores. {{ISBN|978-84-96553-49-1}}</ref> They are smaller than white-nosed coatis from the adjacent mainland (''N. n. yucatanica''), but when compared more widely to white-nosed coatis the difference in size is not as clear.<ref name=Decker/> The level of other differences also support its status as a subspecies rather than separate species.<ref name=Decker/>\n\nWhite-nosed coatis have also been found in the U.S. state of [[Florida]], where they are an introduced species. It is unknown precisely when introduction occurred; an early specimen in the [[Florida Museum of Natural History]], labeled an \"escaped captive\", dates to 1928. There are several later documented cases of coatis escaping captivity, and since the 1970s there have been a number of sightings, and several live and dead specimens of various ages have been found. These reports have occurred over a wide area of southern Florida, and there is probable evidence of breeding, indicating that the population is well established.<ref name=Simberloff>{{cite book |title= Strangers in Paradise: Impact and Management of Nonindigenous Species in Florida|last= Simberloff|first= Daniel|authorlink= Daniel Simberloff|author2=Don C. Schmitz |author3=Tom C. Brown |year= 1997|publisher= Island Press|isbn= 1-55963-430-8|page= 170|url= https://books.google.com/?id=rtrpSllq4SQC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate= 29 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Feeding habits==\n[[File:Nasua narica 02 MWNH 353.JPG|thumb|Skull of a white nosed coati]]\nThey are [[omnivore]]s, preferring small [[vertebrate]]s, [[fruit]]s, [[carrion]], [[insect]]s, [[snake]]s and [[egg (biology)|eggs]]. They can climb trees easily, where the tail is used for balance, but they are most often on the ground foraging. Their predators include [[Boidae|boa]]s, [[Bird of prey|raptor]]s, [[Felidae|hunting cats]], and [[Tayra]]s (''Eira barbara'').  They readily adapt to human presence; like [[raccoon]]s, they will raid campsites and trash receptacles.  They can be tamed easily, and have been verified experimentally to be quite [[Animal cognition|intelligent]].{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\n==Behavior==\n[[File:White nosed Coati.jpg|left|thumb|A white-nosed coati in a [[conservation area]] in [[Arenal Tilaran Conservation Area|Arenal, Costa Rica]]]]\nWhile the [[raccoon]] and ringtail are nocturnal, coatis are [[Diurnality|active by day]], retiring during the night to a specific tree and descending at dawn to begin their daily search for food. However, their habits are adjustable, and in areas where they are hunted by humans for food, or where they raid human settlements for their own food, they might become more [[Nocturnality|nocturnal]].  Adult males are [[Lone wolf (trait)|solitary]], but females and sexually immature males form [[Social unit|social groups]]. They use many vocal signals to [[Animal communication|communicate]] with one another, and also spend time grooming themselves and each other with their teeth and claws. During [[foraging]] times, the young cubs are left with a pair of babysitters, similar to [[meerkat]]s. The young males and even some females tend to [[Play fighting|play-fight]]. Many of the [[coati]]s will have short [[Combat|fights]] over food.{{citation needed|date=November 2016}}\n\nWhite-nosed coatis are known pollinators of the balsa tree, as observed in a study of a white-nosed coati population in Costa Rica. <ref name=Mora>Mora, Jos\u00e9 Manuel. (1999). ''[https://tropicalstudies.org/rbt/attachments/volumes/vol47-4/08_Mora_Nasua_narica.pdf White-nosed coati Nasua narica (Carnivora: Procyonidae) as a potentialpollinator of Ochroma pyramidale (Bombacaceae)].'' Revista de biologia tropical 47(4):719-721</ref> The coati were observed inserting their noses into the flowers of the tree and ingesting nectar, while the flower showed no subsequent signs of damage. Pollen from the flowers covers the face of the coati following feeding, and later disseminates through the surrounding forest following detachment. Scientists observed a dependent relationship between the balsa tree, which provides a critical resource of hydration and nutrition to the white-nosed coati when environment resources are scarce, and the coati, which increases proliferation of the tree through pollination.\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Nasua narica}}\n*[http://www.mnh.si.edu/mna/image_info.cfm?species_id=208 Smithsonian Institution \u2013 North American Mammals: Nasua narica]\n*[http://siwild.si.edu/content/animal-groups/other-carnivores/white-nosed-coati.htm?species=130 Smithsonian Wild: Nasua narica]\n\n{{Procyonidae nav}}\n{{Carnivora|C.}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q754992}}\n\n[[Category:Procyonidae]]\n[[Category:Carnivorans of North America|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Carnivorans of Central America|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Carnivorans of South America|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Colombia|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Costa Rica|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Guatemala|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Mammals of Mexico|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Mammals of the United States|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the Southwestern United States]]\n[[Category:Mammals described in 1766]]\n[[Category:Least concern biota of North America|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Least concern biota of South America|Coati, white-nosed]]\n[[Category:Taxa named by Carl Linnaeus]]\n", "name_user": "Roqz", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBehavior:proper conservation area related to arenal volcano... but might not be an adequate caption at all", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/White-nosed_coati"}
{"title_page": "Kfar Haruv", "text_new": "{{short description|Israeli settlement in the Golan Heights}}\n{{Infobox Kibbutz\n| name = Kfar Haruv\n| image =\n| caption =\n| hebname = {{Hebrew|\u05db\u05b0\u05bc\u05e4\u05b7\u05e8 \u05d7\u05b8\u05e8\u05d5\u05bc\u05d1}}\n| arname =\n| meaning =\n| foundation = 1974\n| founded_by = {{nowrap|[[Hashomer Hatzair]] members}}\n| region = [[Golan Heights]]\n| council = [[Golan Regional Council]]\n| affiliation   = [[Kibbutz Movement]]\n| district = north\n| popyear = {{Israel populations|Year}}\n| population = {{Israel populations|Kefar Haruv}}{{Israel populations|reference}}\n| population_footnotes=\n| pushpin_map=Israel Golan\n| pushpin_mapsize=250\n| pushpin_label_position=bottom\n| coordinates = {{coord|32|45|45|N|35|39|49|E|display=inline,title}}\n| area_dunam=\n| website=\n}}\n\n'''Kfar Haruv''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05db\u05b0\u05bc\u05e4\u05b7\u05e8 \u05d7\u05b8\u05e8\u05d5\u05bc\u05d1}}, ''lit.'' [[Ceratonia siliqua|Carob]] Village) is an [[Israeli settlement]] organized as a [[kibbutz]] located in the southern [[Golan Heights]]. A member of the [[Kibbutz Movement]], it falls under the jurisdiction of [[Golan Regional Council]]. The international community considers Israeli settlements in the Golan Heights [[International law and Israeli settlements|illegal under international law]], but the Israeli government disputes this.<ref name=\"BBC_The_Geneva_Convention\">{{cite news\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/1682640.stm\n| title = The Geneva Convention\n| publisher = [[BBC]]\n| date=10 December 2009\n}}</ref> In {{Israel populations|Year}} it had a population of {{Israel populations|Kefar Haruv}}.{{Israel populations|reference}}\n\n==Geography==\nThe kibbutz is located on the edge of the cliffs {{convert|315|m|ft|sp=us}} above sea level (about {{convert|525|m|ft|sp=us}} above the [[Sea of Galilee]]) and {{convert|2|km|mi|sp=us}} east of the sea.\n\n==History==\nA village called Kfar Yahrib is mentioned in the 3rd century [[Mosaic of Rehob]].<ref name=grandrapids1979 /> Later an Arab village with the similar name ''Kafr Harib'' existed at the south edge of the current settlement's built-up area. Kafr Harib appeared in Ottoman tax registers in 1596 as a village in the ''[[Nahiya]]'' of Jawlan Garbi in the ''[[Liwa (Arabic)|Qada]]'' of Hawran. It had a population of 5 Muslim households and 7 bachelors and paid taxes on wheat, barley and goats or beehives.<ref>{{cite book | author = Wolf-Dieter H\u00fctteroth and Kamal Abdulfattah | title = Historical Geography of Palestine, Transjordan and Southern Syria in the Late 16th Century | year = 1977 | publisher = Erlanger Geographische Arbeiten, Sonderband 5. Erlangen, Germany: Vorstand der Fr\u00e4nkischen Geographischen Gesellschaft | page = 196}}</ref> In 1888, [[Gottlieb Schumacher]] described it as a village of 70 stone and mud huts with about 200 \"affable and hospitable\" inhabitants, who ran an excellent bee industry in addition to cultivation.<ref name=\"Schumacher\">{{cite book | author = G. Schmacher | title = The Jaul\u00e2n | place = London | publisher = Richard Bentley and Son | year = 1888 | page = X}}</ref> Later the village lay just outside the borders of [[Mandatory Palestine]], though some of its lands lay inside Palestine.<ref>Government of Palestine, Village Statistics 1945, p. 12.</ref> Kafr Harib village had about 1900 inhabitants when it was depopulated during the [[Six Day War]] in 1967.<ref name=\"Kipnis\">{{cite book | author = Yigal Kipnis | title = The Golan Heights | publisher = Routledge | place = London and New York | year = 2013 | page = 244}}</ref>\n\nThe Israeli settlement was founded in 1973, and took its name from Kafr Harib.<ref name=grandrapids1979>''The Holy Land - from the Persian to the Arab Conquests (536 B.C. to A.D. 640) A Historical Geography '', [[Michael Avi-Yonah]], Grand Rapids, 1979, p.  170; {{ISBN|0-8010-0010-6}}</ref> The new Israeli founders settled temporarily in Afik camp, and moved to the present-day location (the site of a [[Military of Syria|Syrian army]] base that overlooks [[Ein Gev]] and [[HaOn]]) in 1974. The sixteenth Israeli settlement established in the Golan Heights, its members are native Israelis and immigrants from the [[United States]]. As of 2011 the population stood at 400 residents, of whom 90 live in the new neighborhood built in 2004.\n\n==Economy==\nThe main employer of the settlement is the A.R.I. factory that it owns, which manufactures [[hydraulic]] equipment.  The settlement continues to grow plants for [[agriculture]], such as almonds, avocado, nectars, and peaches. It also has a cow stable for milk.  There is also a laundromat and curtain-maker. The settlement is a partner in the tourist site [[Hamat Gader]], and it operates [[Mitzpe LeShalom]] (Peace Vista), a place for recreation on the edge of the On Cliffs.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Israeli-occupied territories]]\n* [[Status of territories occupied by Israel in 1967]]\n* [[Israeli Military Governorate]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070311014238/http://www2.golan.org.il/ts.exe?tsurl=0.73.16123.0.0 Kfar Haruv] Golan Heights website {{in lang|he}}\n\n{{Golan Regional Council}}\n\n[[Category:Israeli settlements]]\n[[Category:Kibbutzim]]\n[[Category:Kibbutz Movement]]\n[[Category:Golan Regional Council]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1974]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Northern District (Israel)]]\n[[Category:1974 establishments in the Israeli Military Governorate]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Israeli settlement in the Golan Heights}}\n{{Infobox Kibbutz\n| name = Kfar Haruv\n| image =\n| caption =\n| hebname = {{Hebrew|\u05db\u05b0\u05bc\u05e4\u05b7\u05e8 \u05d7\u05b8\u05e8\u05d5\u05bc\u05d1}}\n| arname =\n| meaning =\n| foundation = 1974\n| founded_by = {{nowrap|[[Hashomer Hatzair]] members}}\n| region = [[Golan Heights]]\n| council = [[Golan Regional Council]]\n| affiliation   = [[Kibbutz Movement]]\n| district = north\n| popyear = {{Israel populations|Year}}\n| population = {{Israel populations|Kefar Haruv}}{{Israel populations|reference}}\n| population_footnotes=\n| pushpin_map=Israel Golan\n| pushpin_mapsize=250\n| pushpin_label_position=bottom\n| coordinates = {{coord|32|45|45|N|35|39|49|E|display=inline,title}}\n| area_dunam=\n| website=\n}}\n\n'''Kfar Haruv''' ({{lang-he-n|\u05db\u05b0\u05bc\u05e4\u05b7\u05e8 \u05d7\u05b8\u05e8\u05d5\u05bc\u05d1}}, ''lit.'' [[Ceratonia siliqua|Carob]] Village) is an [[Israeli settlement]] organized as a [[kibbutz]] located in the southern [[Golan Heights]]. A member of the [[Kibbutz Movement]], it falls under the jurisdiction of [[Golan Regional Council]]. The international community considers Israeli settlements in the Golan Heights [[International law and Israeli settlements|illegal under international law]], but the Israeli government disputes this.<ref name=\"BBC_The_Geneva_Convention\">{{cite news\n| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/middle_east/1682640.stm\n| title = The Geneva Convention\n| publisher = [[BBC]]\n| date=10 December 2009\n}}</ref> In {{Israel populations|Year}} it had a population of {{Israel populations|Kefar Haruv}}.{{Israel populations|reference}}\n\n==Geography==\nThe kibbutz is located on the edge of the cliffs {{convert|315|m|ft|sp=us}} above sea level (about {{convert|525|m|ft|sp=us}} above the [[Sea of Galilee]]) and {{convert|2|km|mi|sp=us}} east of the sea.\n\n==History==\nA village called Kfar Yahrib is mentioned in the 3rd century [[Mosaic of Rehob]].<ref name=grandrapids1979 /> Later an Arab village with the similar name ''Kafr Harib'' existed at the south edge of the current settlement's built-up area. Kafr Harib appeared in Ottoman tax registers in 1596 as a village in the ''[[Nahiya]]'' of Jawlan Garbi in the ''[[Liwa (Arabic)|Qada]]'' of Hawran.  It had a population of 5 Muslim households and 7 bachelors and paid taxes on wheat, barley and goats or beehives.<ref>{{cite book | author = Wolf-Dieter H\u00fctteroth and Kamal Abdulfattah | title = Historical Geography of Palestine, Transjordan and Southern Syria in the Late 16th Century | year = 1977 | publisher = Erlanger Geographische Arbeiten, Sonderband 5. Erlangen, Germany: Vorstand der Fr\u00e4nkischen Geographischen Gesellschaft | page = 196}}</ref> In 1888, [[Gottlieb Schumacher]] described it as a village of 70 stone and mud huts with about 200 \"affable and hospitable\" inhabitants, who ran an excellent bee industry in addition to cultivation.<ref name=\"Schumacher\">{{cite book | author = G. Schmacher | title = The Jaul\u00e2n | place = London | publisher = Richard Bentley and Son | year = 1888 | page = X}}</ref> Later the village lay just outside the borders of [[Mandatory Palestine]], though some of its lands lay inside Palestine.<ref>Government of Palestine, Village Statistics 1945, p. 12.</ref> Kafr Harib village had about 1900 inhabitants when it was depopulated during the [[Six Day War]] in 1967.<ref name=\"Kipnis\">{{cite book | author = Yigal Kipnis | title = The Golan Heights | publisher = Routledge | place = London and New York | year = 2013 | page = 244}}</ref>\n\nThe Israeli settlement was founded in 1973, and took its name from Kafr Harib.<ref name=grandrapids1979>''The Holy Land - from the Persian to the Arab Conquests (536 B.C. to A.D. 640) A Historical Geography '', [[Michael Avi-Yonah]], Grand Rapids, 1979, p.  170; {{ISBN|0-8010-0010-6}}</ref> The new Israeli founders settled temporarily in Afik camp, and moved to the present-day location (the site of a [[Military of Syria|Syrian army]] base that overlooks [[Ein Gev]] and [[HaOn]]) in 1974. The sixteenth Israeli settlement established in the Golan Heights, its members are native Israelis and immigrants from the [[United States]]. As of 2011 the population stood at 400 residents, of whom 90 live in the new neighborhood built in 2004.\n\n==Economy==\nThe main employer of the settlement is the A.R.I. factory that it owns, which manufactures [[hydraulic]] equipment.  The settlement continues to grow plants for [[agriculture]], such as almonds, avocado, nectars, and peaches. It also has a cow stable for milk.  There is also a laundromat and curtain-maker. The settlement is a partner in the tourist site [[Hamat Gader]], and it operates [[Mitzpe LeShalom]] (Peace Vista), a place for recreation on the edge of the On Cliffs.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Israeli-occupied territories]]\n* [[Status of territories occupied by Israel in 1967]]\n* [[Israeli Military Governorate]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070311014238/http://www2.golan.org.il/ts.exe?tsurl=0.73.16123.0.0 Kfar Haruv] Golan Heights website {{in lang|he}}\n\n{{Golan Regional Council}}\n\n[[Category:Israeli settlements]]\n[[Category:Kibbutzim]]\n[[Category:Kibbutz Movement]]\n[[Category:Golan Regional Council]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1974]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Northern District (Israel)]]\n[[Category:1974 establishments in the Israeli Military Governorate]]\n", "name_user": "Zarcademan123456", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kfar_Haruv"}
{"title_page": "Ambra Polidori", "text_new": "'''Ambra Polidori''' (born 1954 in [[Mexico City]], Mexico)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latinamericanart.com/en/artist/ambra-polidori/|title=Ambra Polidori|website=Latin American Art|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> is a [[Mexicans|Mexican]] artist, who through diverse genres of the fine arts, such as [[photography]], [[Installation art|installation]], and [[video]], makes a call for attention to the political and social situations of human suffering that arise as a result of the present conflicts.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Heirs of Frida and Diego; Modern Mexican Art Assumes a Worldly Air\n|newspaper=The Washington Post - Washington, D.C.\n|first=Jessica |last=Dawson\n|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/802150511.html?dids=802150511:802150511&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Mar+03%2C+2005&author=Jessica+Dawson&pub=The+Washington+Post&desc=The+Heirs+of+Frida+and+Diego%3B+Modern+Mexican+Art+Assumes+a+Worldly+Air}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2005/01/30/a02n1cul.php |title=El di\u00e1logo del arte mexicano con el exterior ha sido fluido y continuo |publisher=Jornada.unam.mx |date=2005-01-30 |accessdate=2011-02-04}}</ref><ref name=Luis-MartinLozano >{{citation | author=Luis-Marin Lozano | title=In the 90's: Mexican contemporary art | publisher=Institutos Culturales de M\u00e9xico  | page=136 }}</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions ==\nThe work of Ambra Polidori has been exhibited in various places, including:\n\n2011 - ''Disagreements'' (Desacuerdos), Fototeca de Cuba, [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arteporexcelencias.com/en/articles/ambra-polidori-havana|title=Ambra Polidori in Havana {{!}} Arte por Excelencias|website=www.arteporexcelencias.com|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n2001 - The [[Leon Trotsky Museum, Mexico City|Leon Trotsky Museum]] (Museo Casa de Le\u00f3n Trotsky), Mexico City, [[Mexico]]\n\n2001 - [[El Museo del Barrio]], [[New York City|New York]], [[United States]]\n\n2000 - [[Schloss Stra\u00dfburg]], [[Strassburg]], [[Austria]]\n\n2000 - In the traveling show \"Contemporary Art from Mexico\" in [[Cologne]], [[Berlin]] and [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]]\n\n1998 - The Museo de Arte Carrillo Gil (Carrillo Gil Art Museum), Mexico City, Mexico\n\n== Collections ==\nAmbra Polidori's works are included in the following public collections:\n\nJumex Collection\n\nMuseum of Modern Art\n\n[[Biblioth\u00e8que nationale de France|Biblioteque Nationale]], Par\u00eds, France<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://revistareplicante.com/colaboradores/ambra-polidori/|title=Ambra Polidori|date=2018-01-11|website=Revista Replicante|language=es|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\nMuseo Universitario de Arte Contemporaneo (MUCA)\n\nMuseo de Arte Carrillo Gil, Mexico City, Mexico\n\nEl Museo del Barrio, [[New York City|New York]], NY, USA\n\nMaison Europ\u00e9nne de la Photographie (European House of Photography), [[Paris]], [[France]]\n\n[[Banco de Espa\u00f1a]], [[Madrid]], [[Spain]]\n\nAcademia Carrar\n\nGalleria d\u2019Arte Moderna e Contemporanea (Gallery of Modern and Contemporary Art), [[Bergamo]], [[Italy]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Polidori, Ambra}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mexican photographers]]\n[[Category:Mexican women photographers]]\n[[Category:Mexican people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:People from Mexico City]]\n\n\n{{Mexico-artist-stub}}\n{{photographer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Ambra Polidori''' (born 1954 in [[Mexico City]], Mexico)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latinamericanart.com/en/artist/ambra-polidori/|title=Ambra Polidori|website=Latin American Art|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref> is a [[Mexicans|Mexican]] artist, who through diverse genres of the fine arts, such as [[photography]], [[Installation art|installation]], and [[video]], makes a call for attention to the political and social situations of human suffering that arise as a result of the present conflicts.<ref>{{cite news|title=The Heirs of Frida and Diego; Modern Mexican Art Assumes a Worldly Air\n|newspaper=The Washington Post - Washington, D.C.\n|first=Jessica |last=Dawson\n|url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/washingtonpost/access/802150511.html?dids=802150511:802150511&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=Mar+03%2C+2005&author=Jessica+Dawson&pub=The+Washington+Post&desc=The+Heirs+of+Frida+and+Diego%3B+Modern+Mexican+Art+Assumes+a+Worldly+Air}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jornada.unam.mx/2005/01/30/a02n1cul.php |title=El di\u00e1logo del arte mexicano con el exterior ha sido fluido y continuo |publisher=Jornada.unam.mx |date=2005-01-30 |accessdate=2011-02-04}}</ref><ref name=Luis-MartinLozano >{{citation | author=Luis-Marin Lozano | title=In the 90's: Mexican contemporary art | publisher=Institutos Culturales de M\u00e9xico  | page=136 }}</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions ==\nThe work of Ambra Polidori has been exhibited in various places, including:\n\n2011 - ''Disagreements'' (Desacuerdos), Fototeca de Cuba, [[Havana]], [[Cuba]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arteporexcelencias.com/en/articles/ambra-polidori-havana|title=Ambra Polidori in Havana {{!}} Arte por Excelencias|website=www.arteporexcelencias.com|access-date=2020-04-23}}</ref>\n\n2001 - The [[Leon Trotsky Museum, Mexico City|Leon Trotsky Museum]] (Museo Casa de Le\u00f3n Trotsky), Mexico City, [[Mexico]]\n\n2001 - [[El Museo del Barrio]], [[New York City|New York]], [[United States]]\n\n2000 - [[Schloss Stra\u00dfburg]], [[Strassburg]], [[Austria]]\n\n2000 - In the traveling show \"Contemporary Art from Mexico\" in [[Cologne]], [[Berlin]] and [[Budapest]], [[Hungary]]\n\n1998 - The Museo de Arte Carrillo Gil (Carrillo Gil Art Museum), Mexico City, Mexico\n\n== Collections ==\nAmbra Polidori's works are included in the following public collections:\n\nJumex Collection\n\nMuseum of Modern Art\n\nMuseo Universitario de Arte Contemporaneo (MUCA)\n\nMuseo de Arte Carrillo 